2 THE HALO ACT
3 SECTION 6.1.(a) Article 30 of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes is amended by
4 adding a new section to read:
5 "§ 14-223.1. Approaching a first responder with specified intent after a warning.
6 (a) Definitions. – For purposes of this section, the following definitions apply:
7 (1) First responder. – Means any of the following:
8 a. A law enforcement officer.
9 b. A firefighter.
10 c. An emergency medical technician or a medical responder.
11 d. A probation or parole officer.
12 e. A person whose employment duties include the custody,
13 transportation, or management of persons who are detained or
14 confined to a detention facility, youth development center, or
15 correctional institution operated under the jurisdiction of the State or
16 a local government.
17 (2) Harass. – To willfully engage in a course of conduct directed at a first
18 responder which intentionally causes substantial emotional distress in that
19 first responder and serves no legitimate purpose. Merely taking photographs
20 or recording a first responder without another overt act shall not be included
21 in this definition.
22 (b) Offense. – It is unlawful for a person, after receiving a verbal warning not to approach
23 from a person he or she knows or reasonably should know is a first responder, who is engaged in
24 the lawful performance of a legal duty, to knowingly and willfully violate the warning and
25 approach or remain within 25 feet of the first responder with the intent to do any of the following:
26 (1) Impede or interfere with the first responder's ability to perform his or her duty.
27 (2) Threaten the first responder with physical harm.
28 (3) Harass the first responder.
29 Merely taking photographs or recording a first responder without another overt act shall not
30 constitute a violation of this subsection.
31 (c) Punishment. – Unless the conduct is covered under some other provision of law
32 providing greater punishment, a person who violates subsection (b) of this section is guilty of a
33 Class 2 misdemeanor."
34 SECTION 6.1.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2026, and applies to
35 offenses committed on or after that date.
