24 SECTION 10.2.(b) G.S. 14-100 reads as rewritten:
25 "§ 14-100. Obtaining property by false pretenses.
26 (a) If any person shall knowingly and designedly by means of any kind of false pretense
27 whatsoever, whether the false pretense is of a past or subsisting fact or of a future fulfillment or
28 event, obtain or attempt to obtain from any person within this State any money, goods, property,
29 services, chose in action, rental housing or lodging, or other thing of value with intent to cheat or
30 defraud any person of such money, goods, property, services, chose in action action, rental
31 housing or lodging, or other thing of value, such person shall be guilty of a felony: Provided, that
32 if, on the trial of anyone indicted for such crime, it shall be proved that he obtained the property
33 in such manner as to amount to larceny or embezzlement, the jury shall have submitted to them
34 such other felony proved; and no person tried for such felony shall be liable to be afterwards
35 prosecuted for larceny or embezzlement upon the same facts: Provided, further, that it shall be
36 sufficient in any indictment for obtaining or attempting to obtain any such money, goods,
37 property, services, chose in action, or other thing of value by false pretenses to allege that the
38 party accused did the act with intent to defraud, without alleging an intent to defraud any
39 particular person, and without alleging any ownership of the money, goods, property, services,
40 chose in action or other thing of value; and upon the trial of any such indictment, it shall not be
41 necessary to prove either an intent to defraud any particular person or that the person to whom
42 the false pretense was made was the person defrauded, but it shall be sufficient to allege and
43 prove that the party accused made the false pretense charged with an intent to defraud. If the
44 value of the money, goods, property, services, chose in action, or other thing of value is one
45 hundred thousand dollars ($100,000) or more, a violation of this section is a Class C felony. If
46 the value of the money, goods, property, services, chose in action, or other thing of value is less
47 than one hundred thousand dollars ($100,000), a violation of this section is a Class H felony.
48 (b) Evidence of nonfulfillment of a contract obligation standing alone shall not establish
49 the essential element of intent to defraud.
50 (b1) In any prosecution for violation of this section, the State is not required to establish
51 that all of the acts constituting the crime occurred in this State or within a single city, county, or
