19 EXPUNCTIONS RELATED TO LAW ENFORCEMENT CERTIFICATION
20 SECTION 16.(a) G.S. 17C-13 reads as rewritten:
21 "§ 17C-13. Pardons; expunctions.
22 (a) When a person presents competent evidence that he has been granted an unconditional
23 pardon for a crime in this State, any other state, or the United States, the Commission may not
24 deny, suspend, or revoke that person's certification based solely on the commission of that crime
25 or for an alleged lack of good moral character due to the commission of that crime.
26 (b) Notwithstanding G.S. 15A-145.4 or G.S. 15A-145.5, the Commission may gain
27 access to a person's felony conviction records, including those maintained by the Administrative
28 Office of the Courts in its confidential files containing the names of persons granted expunctions.
29 The Commission may deny, suspend, or revoke a person's certification based solely on that
30 person's felony conviction, whether or not that conviction was expunged, unless the conviction
31 was expunged pursuant to G.S. 15A-145.4 or G.S. 15A-145.8A.
32 (c) Except as provided by this section, the Commission may deny, suspend, or revoke a
33 person's certification based on commission of a crime regardless of whether the charge or
34 conviction was expunged. Commission of the offense may be proven by testimony, documents,
35 personnel files (including personnel investigation reports), criminal histories, and any other
36 relevant evidence.
37 (d) Unless an order of expunction was granted pursuant to G.S. 15A-145.4 or
38 G.S. 15A-145.8A, consistent with this section, the Commission may deny, suspend, or revoke a
39 person's certification based upon failure to disclose, recite, report, or acknowledge an expunged
40 arrest, apprehension, charge, indictment, information, trial, or conviction."
41 SECTION 16.(b) G.S. 17E-12 reads as rewritten:
42 "§ 17E-12. Pardons; expunctions.
43 (a) When a person presents competent evidence that the person has been granted an
44 unconditional pardon of innocence for a crime in this State, any other state, or the United States,
45 the Commission may not deny, suspend, or revoke that person's certification based solely on the
46 commission of that crime or for alleged lack of good moral character due to the commission of
47 that crime.
48 (b) Notwithstanding G.S. 15A-145.4 or G.S. 15A-145.5, the Commission may gain
49 access to a person's felony conviction records, including those maintained by the Administrative
50 Office of the Courts in its confidential files containing the names of persons granted expunctions.
51 The Commission may deny, suspend, or revoke a person's certification based solely on that
Page 14 House Bill 308-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 person's felony conviction, whether or not that conviction was expunged, unless the conviction
2 was expunged pursuant to G.S. 15A-145.4 or G.S. 15A-145.8A.
3 (c) Except as provided by this section, the Commission may deny, suspend, or revoke a
4 person's certification based on commission of a crime regardless of whether the charge or
5 conviction was expunged. Commission of the offense may be proven by testimony, documents,
6 personnel files (including personnel investigation reports), criminal histories, and any other
7 relevant evidence."
8 SECTION 16.(c) This section is effective when it becomes law.
